TFT Augments and Traits: Set 6.5 Patch 12.8¶

CMSC320 Final Project¶

Kyle Sang, Gary Zhang¶

Overview¶

Teamfight Tactics (TFT) is an auto-chess battling game designed by Riot Games. In the game, you build a team of units to battle 7 other players for a placement 1-8 and a chance to earn some juicy LP, the points that make up TFT's ranking system. In the game, these units have two or three different traits, which grant bonuses if you acquire enough units of the same trait. These traits generally have 4 levels to them, with some exceptions which we will consider further dodwn the line. Throughout the game, you also receive a chance to pick an augment, a passive effect that improves the performance of your team, a total of three times. In this project, we would like to observe the effects different augments have on the average placement of a player, based on the active traits that the player has upon the conclusion of the game.

First we import the necessary libraries that we will use in this project. Pandas dataframes will be used to store and process the data, the numpy library will provide useful fuctionality when working with our data, Matplotlib will be our primary method of plotting data, and the default dict from python's collections library will be a useful tool for storing our data.

Data Collection¶

In order to gather data on TFT matches, we need a way to query Riot Game's API. To accomplish this, we will use the riotwatcher library. The riotwatcher library is a light wrapper that facilitates querying the Riot API

from riotwatcher import TftWatcher, ApiError

In order to query the Riot API, we also need an API key. For our purposes, a personal API key suffices. This key limits the refresh rates of queries to 100 requests per 2 minutes. This makes data collecting somewhat slow, but works as intended for our purposes. If you have a product that requires a higher request rate, you can apply for a production key that allows for 30,000 requests every 10 minutes. In general, these keys require a working prototype of the product you are working one. In the below code, the watcher sets you up to connect to the TFT API servers, and region specifies the North American region, where our Riot accounts were located. Note that for developer keys, you must have a Riot account which you can make for free, and that the region you use must be the same as the region of your Riot account.

In [186]:
api_key = 'RGAPI-c107eb23-f0cf-4d15-9d92-232baecafe96' # key
watcher = TftWatcher(api_key)
region = 'na1'

For our purposes, we will look at the upper echelons of competitive TFT, the challenger rank. This rank consists of the region's top 250 players. To obtain the challenger data, we use riotwatcher to obtain the challengers in the North American region, and store their names inside the list names. For each challenger in this name list, we obtained their last 10 matches. First we had to obtain the summoner and then use their puuid to obtain a list of their last 10 matches all using the riotwatcher library. After obtaining this list of matches, we iterate through them and put them into a set. This is to ensure that there is no repetition in our matches, since the top ranked players likely play matches against other top matched players. In this way, we are able to generate a list of unique match ids from which we can obtain data. The try-catch was to catch a user who likely changed his name. This change was likely reflected in the League API, but not yet updated in the TFT API, resulting in an exception.

In [27]:
challengers = watcher.league.challenger(region)
names = list()
match_set = set()

for entry in challengers['entries']:
    names.append(entry["summonerName"])

for name in names:
    try
        summoner = watcher.summoner.by_name(region, name)
        matches = watcher.match.by_puuid(region, summoner['puuid'], 10)
        for match in matches:
            match_set.add(match)
    except:
        print(name)

In total, we had 1676 unique games, a decent amount lower than the 2500 matches we obtained by multiplying the 250 challengers by 10 matches.

Next, we convert our match set into a list to facilitate iterating through it. For each match in the list, we obtain the in game info that we are interested in. First we declare the rows variable, which will be a list of lists from which we can generate a dataframe. Next we acquire the matches data by id using the riotwatcher api. This data is formatted in nested dictionary formats. The information we were interested in were located in the info, and then participant keys. Accessing these values from the match dictionary, we obtain the 8 players that played in that particular match. We iterate through these players and gather information on their team compositions, including their active traits, augments chosen, and their placement.

While obtaining this data, we noted the level of the trait that each person had by the "style" characteristics within the traits dictionary, which was indicated by a number 0 through 4. 0 indicated that the trait was not present, while 1 through 4 represented the ranking, bronze, silver, gold, and prismatic respectively, with prismatic as the highest tier and bronze the lowest. For our purposes, we considered traits with style 2 and above to be present in final compositions. This is because to obtain a style 2-4 trait requires a certain amount of commitment to the trait by fielding several units of that trait.

Note that this part of the project took the longest time to run due to the low refresh rate of the producer API key. Running the following code took roughly 20 minutes.

In [ ]:
match_list = list(match_set)
rows = list()

for match_id in match_list:
    try:
        match = watcher.match.by_id(region, match_id)

        participants = match['info']['participants']
        augments = list()
        for participant in participants:
            row = [0] * 28
            augment = participant['augments'] #list
            traits = participant['traits']
            for trait in traits:
                trait_indice = trait_names.index(trait['name'])
                row[trait_indice] = trait['style']
            row = row + augment
            row.append(participant['placement'])
            rows.append(row)
    except:
        print(match_id)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Traits and Their Average Placement¶

The first bit of data analysis we would like to perform is how traits on their own compare to one another in regards to their average placements.

We create a dictionary trait_placement that has as its key the trait, and as the value a tuple of the average placement of this trait and the number of games played of this trait. At this point, we also exclude the one-off traits. We do this since the one-off traits are not very indicative of the builds that players generate. Usually they are included on end game units that you would not build your team around, and so are not very interesting when looking at augment picks which are chosen throughout the game. Throughout this process we only observe traits with style values greater than or equal to two for reasons stated in our Data Management/Representation section.

In [10]:
trait_placement = dict()

for trait in trait_names:
    if trait not in one_off_traits:
        trait_placement[trait] = (df.loc[df[trait] >= 2, 'Placement'].mean(), df.loc[df[trait] >= 2, 'Placement'].count())

Pickrate vs Average Placement of Augments¶

Next, we will look at the pickrate and average placement of different augments.

First, we create a default dictionary with an empty list as the default value to contain our data. Then, for each row in our dataframe, we scan through each augment in the "Augment_1", "Augment_2", and "Augment_3" and add the placement of the row to the corresponding list in the dictionary. By the end of this process, we have a dictionary with its keys as the augments, and the values as lists containing all the placements of different augments

In [13]:
augments_winrate = defaultdict( lambda: [] )

for index, row in df.iterrows():
    for augment in ['Augment_1', 'Augment_2', 'Augment_3']:
        if type(row[augment]) != float:
            augments_winrate[row[augment]].append(row['Placement'])

Next, we create code to generate the data we will use to plot the graph based on this dictionary. First, we create three lists, x to keep track of the pickrate, y to keep track of the average placement, and keys to keep track of which augment corresponds to each pickrate and average placement. Then, we iterate through the dictionary, adding to these respective lists. Keys will simply add the key of the dictionary entry, x will receive the pickrate as a percentage by dividing the number of placements by the total number of boards observed, and y will append the average of the list within the value of the dictionary.

Augments and Their Placements for Each Trait¶

For each trait in the traits we are interested in (those not contained in the one off traits) we wish to have a way to visually see the best and worst augments for that trait. Thus, we will generate the graphs for several different traits, plotting the augments that had a sample size greater than thirty for that trait and the average placement of the augments.

First we get the list of the traits we are interested in and store it into real_traits. We also declare a list of lists data_array which will store rows for a new dataframe. Then for each trait in this list, we filter the dataframe for rows only containing the trait at a style 2 or greater. Next, we create a dictionary that will have as its keys the augments, and its values dictionaries. These sub dictionaries will all contain two entries, one accessible by 'count' which keeps track of number of occurrences, and one accessible by 'placement' which contains the sum of all the placements of the augments. Then, for each entry we check that the count is over 30, and add a list to the data_array containing the trait, augment, and average placement. At the end, we have a list of lists of every augment trait combination with more than 30 games played. We then convert this into the dataframe aug_rank to more easily graph the data. The reason we check that the number of games is over 30 is so that we know we have a statistically significant amount of games played for each trait augment pair.

In [18]:
real_traits = [trait for trait in trait_names if trait not in one_off_traits]
data_array = list()
for trait in real_traits:
    trait_df = df[df[trait] >= 2]

    augment_freq = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))
    for index, row in trait_df.iterrows():
         for augment in ['Augment_1', 'Augment_2', 'Augment_3']:
            if type(row[augment]) != float:
                augment_freq[row[augment]]['count'] += 1
                augment_freq[row[augment]]['placement'] += row['Placement']

    for key, value in augment_freq.items():
        if value['count'] >= 30:
            new_row = list()
            new_row.append(trait)
            new_row.append(key)
            new_row.append(value['placement'] / value['count'])
            data_array.append(new_row)

aug_rank = pd.DataFrame(data = data_array, columns = ['Trait', 'Augment', 'Average Placement'])

Next is code to graph the dataframe we generated above. We accomplish this by using pandas groupby function on the attribute 'Trait'. For readability's sake, we will only graph those traits which have five or more augments with more than 30 games. This is largely due to the fact that Matplotlib warns when you have too many graphs open. Next we plot the graphs as bar graphs, with augments with placements better than average in the color blue and those with placements worse than average in the color red. We also draw a dotted line indicating the average winrate for each trait.

Hypothesis Testing¶

For our hypothesis testing, we decided to look at whether or not the best augment for each trait placement wise truly had an effect on the placement of a player playing such a trait. Thus, our null hypothesis was such that the population mean of the trait is equal to the sample mean of the trait when it has the augment, and our alternative hypothesis was such that the sample mean of the trait is lower than that of the population mean. Because of this lower than trait, we ended up performing a left tailed z test. The formula to calculate the z statistic was the $\frac{sample mean - population mean}{\frac{population standard deviation}{\sqrt{sample count}}}$. We then used the scipy stats library in order to generate pvalues based on this z statistic, and compared it with the value 0.05. The pvalue represents the chance of a result occuring given the null hypothesis to be true, so a chance lower than 5 percent we deemed to be a small enough value to safely reject the null hypothesis, and establish a correlation between the highest winrate augment and the winpercentage of a certain trait.

import math
import scipy.stats

for trait, grp in aug_rank.groupby(['Trait']):
    print(f'Null Hypothesis for {trait} \n H0:\u03BC = {trait_placement[trait][0]}')
    print(f'Alternative Hypothesis for {trait} \n Ha: \u03BC < {trait_placement[trait][0]}')
    
    aug = grp.loc[grp["Average Placement"].idxmin()]["Augment"]

    std = df[(df[trait] >= 2) & ((df['Augment_1'] == aug) | (df['Augment_2'] == aug) | (df['Augment_3'] == aug))]['Placement'].std()
    mean = aug_rank[(aug_rank['Trait'] == trait) & (aug_rank['Augment'] == aug)]['Average Placement']
    count = len(df[(df[trait] >= 2) & ((df['Augment_1'] == aug) | (df['Augment_2'] == aug) | (df['Augment_3'] == aug))])
    
    zstat = (mean - trait_placement[trait][0]) / (std / math.sqrt(count))
    pval = scipy.stats.norm.sf(abs(zstat))
   
    if pval <= 0.05:
        print(f'pvalue {pval} <= 0.05: Null hypothesis rejected')
    else:
        print(f'pvalue {pval} > 0.05: Null hypothesis rejected')

Summary¶

Introduction¶

With this project we set out to determine which augments are the best, and in what situation. In a game of TFT there are 8 players with a board of troops. Each troop has attributes called traits. Having more troops of the same trait increases the level of that trait, giving certain troops bonuses. There are also augments which are special passive bonuses given to your entire team. You fight until there is only 1 person left standing.

Data Collection¶

To retrieve data from the TFT servers, we used Riots API to obtain the information. The documentation for Riots API can be found here. However, we ran into an issue with the ease of access to the code. As a result, we also decided to utilize a thin wrapper known as RiotWatcher to make sending requests to Riots servers easier.The RiotWatcher documentation can be found here Using this we obtained data from challenger level players on which team compositions were best. We chose to look at challengers for two specific reasons. One, challengers are the highest level of players, with this in mind, the team compositions they use and play against are likely the most optimal. If this is the case, our data shows the performance of certain augments against the highest levels of play. If we were to include data from lower ranks, it could give an inaccurate representation on the efficacy of an augment in higher levels of play. Certain augments are difficult to understand, and may have ineffective use at lower ranks. Others may be extremely effective at lower ranks because players dont know their counterplay. Overall, our goal was to find which augments are the best to use, and you dont learn what is optimal by watching unskilled players. Two, we also were limited by the personal keys Riot provides to personal accounts. Ideally, we wouldve used data from grandmaster and master as well (the two ranks below challenger). With challenger, which there are only 250 of, we looked at eachs past 10 games and were only able to find 1676 unique games. From that, there are 8 team compositions, each with 3 augments, in each game. From that we have around 13000 unique team compositions, but because there are around 140 augments, we were not able to find reliable data for the performance of each augment with one of the 27 available traits. By not including other ranks, we lose the opportunity to view more unconventional strategies, as most challengers will only play the most optimal strategies. As a result, we have an abundance of data on popular compositions with popular augments, but know less about the interaction between unorthodox compositions and augments. Additionally, we dont know if there are any exploitable augments that work in lower skill brackets by looking at challenger data. After sending requesting the data, each game was formatted as a bunch of nested dictionaries. From each game we extracted three main categories: augments, traits, and placement. We extracted augments and traits because we obviously want to see the relationship between the two. We extracted placements as an indicator of how well a team composition and augment did. Its important to note you can place 1 - 8, the lower the number the better.

Data Management¶

For our data management, we turned the list of lists we gathered into a dataframe. In the dataframe we kept track of every team composition (8 per game), which includes the 28 traits, the 3 augments they chose, and their placement that match. For each of the 28 traits, the number represents style, or the level they were at. The more dedicated your team is into achieving a certain trait, the higher the number. We formatted our dataframe to have each trait in a separate column due to the fact that you could have a variable number of traits at a variable level of prevalence. By having them in separate columns, we could much more easily and efficiently parse through our data. The augments did not get put into separate columns, however, as there are too many and each player always has three. Unless in the case of them surrendering early, in which case the augments not chosen (you choose throughout the game) are nan values. Additionally, surrendering also makes the placement nan, so we decided to impute 8s for any surrenders. We did this because most players will not surrender since there isnt an incentive to. Surrenders will usually only happen at the beginning of a game, which would automatically make a player place 8th.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

For our exploratory data analysis, we wanted to see the winrates of each trait, which represent general team composition. We decided that level 2 or higher was representative of a trait being important, as reaching level 2 meant around 50% of your troops were dedicated towards that trait. In general, most comps will only have 1 or 2 traits above level 1 active at a time. From this, we know that if a trait is level 2 or higher it is representative of the team composition. Additionally, we filtered certain traits that special legendary units will activate. These traits are labeled as level 3 in the API, but only take one unit to activate. As a result, we deemed these traits not representative of team composition. For each row of our dataframe, if the trait met the conditions discussed above, we would count the placement of that row towards the mean winrate of that trait. As the graph shows, most of the traits hover around placing 4.5, however, certain compositions placed differently. Certain traits, such as Mercenary, placed much worse due to their nature. This trait rewards dying, and gives you the resources to change to a different composition. Ending the game with this trait active likely means a player did not reach the opportunity to change to a different composition. Others, such as Scholar, placed much higher, which may be due to the fact they were the most effective during that version of the game. However, it is also important to note that Scholar and other traits like it often had a lower sample size. Traits with higher sample size were much closer to 4.5, even though they were considered the strongest at the time. As shown by our next graph, the playmates of each composition was extremely different. The graph after that one, also focuses on pickrate versus winrate for augments. As can be observed, as pickrate increases the winrate converges to 4.5. However, if pickrate is low the winrate is much more variable for the different augments. Lastly, we did an analysis of winrates for each trait based on augment. For each trait, we looked at the winrates of different augments when that trait was specifically active. Additionally, the number of games we looked at had to be above 30, or else we considered the sample to be too potentially inaccurate. We also only included the traits with at least 5 augments that met these requirements, in order to save on space and improve readability (note that we still do hypothesis tests on all augments). We also included a line that showed that traits average winrate. Augments that had below average performance were marked to indicate their ineffectiveness.

Hypothesis Testing¶

For our hypothesis tests, we chose to do a z-test for the highest winrate augment for each trait (as long as it showed up at least 30 times) in order to determine whether or not the augment was having a significant effect on winrate. We didnt look at all augments as we decided that may muddle up readability, and we just want to confirm whether or not augment choice is important. We chose a z-test because we guaranteed that there was at least 30 matches so we could apply CLT, but also we did not know the population variance. We set the null hypothesis to the average winrate of the trait we were analyzing to see whether or not we found a significant difference in winrate for specific augments. After performing the z-test with a 95% confidence, we rejected every null hypothesis and found statistically significant evidence to support that choosing the augment does have an impact on placement.

Communication of Insights¶

From our data there are many insights we can communicate. When it comes to augments or team compositions, the mean winrate hovers around 4.5 when the sampling is large enough. Even for augments, such as portable forge, that generally had we can this we can see that augment clearly has an impact on the performance of any given composition. We also noticed that augments like portable forge still had winrates near 4.5, despite popularity and community agreement that it was one of the best augments. More importantly, however, is we found evidence to prove the effect of augments on the winrate of certain team compositions. With this knowledge, we can then apply our earlier findings to determine which augments are best. If we did not reject the null hypothesis, we would not able to use any of the data from our relationship analysis between winrate, augment, and trait. Luckily, we can look at which augments are best for which traits. For certain traits, such as sniper, the best augments are not surprising. Snipers are best with snipers nest which just boosts their damage. However, for other traits such as syndicates, the answer is not so simple. For syndicates, the best is sniper emblem, which increases the amount of snipers you have. The syndicate and sniper traits only overlap with one unit Ashe, so why is sniper so important? What is likely happening is syndicates require a lot of units to activate, so there isnt much room for other snipers besides Ashe. However, without another sniper, the bonus does not activate. As a result, getting a sniper emblem lets a player have enough troop space to fit syndicates, but also gain the sniper buff. Many of the other trait and augment combinations also have complex reasons in why they are effective or not. Unfortunately, our data only shows the most optimal augment for a trait, and not why its effective. However, this data would still be very advantageous to anyone trying to improve their chances of winning. In terms of usage, this data is very important for players and Riot themselves. Players can use this data to see which team compositions are best with which augments, as well as even dispel community misconceptions on which augments are best. For Riot, this also helps to prove which augments are too strong or weak and for which traits when considering game balancing. Overall, this data can be used by many different individuals.

Potential Error¶

It is important to note that augments show up at different rates and each player is only given a selection of 3. As a result, we may have missed certain augments that are actually genuinely optimal, but did not have enough data to be considered. Additionally, since the game is patched every few weeks the data we have shown above may be drastically different in a few weeks time.

Thanks for reading!
